Clean NYCSB data regressions

2024-02-05

Clean data regressions - Idling energy consumption analysis

Installing packages

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(jtools)

Importing the data

df <- read_csv("esb_cleaned.csv")

Comparing total distance registered and odometer distance

df <- df %>% 
  mutate(odometer_distance = `Final Odometer`- `Initial Odometer`,
         distance_difference = `Total Distance` - odometer_distance)

hist(df$distance_difference,
     main = "Distance difference between Total distance and Odometer calculated",
     xlab = "Distance difference (in miles)")

Testing average bus speed

df <- df %>% 
  mutate(speed=`Total Distance`/`Driving Time`)

hist(df$speed,
     main = "Average speed distribution",
     xlab = "Speed (in mph)")

Cleaning the data to leave only those with distance difference < |5|. GL is the only region with Fuel fired heater and does not have odometer information. We kept all GL data for comparison.

df_clean <- df %>% 
  filter(Region == "GL" | (Region != "GL" & distance_difference < abs(5)))

Filtering for those with electric heater only

df_electric_heater <- df_clean %>% 
  filter(`Fuel Fired Heater?`==FALSE)

Filtering for each region

GL_data <- df_clean %>% 
  filter(Region=="GL")

NC_data <- df_clean %>% 
  filter(Region=="NC")

RM_data <- df_clean %>% 
  filter(Region=="RM")

SC_data <- df_clean %>% 
  filter(Region=="SC")

Homogeneity data analsys

Cross Regions comparison

Creating the data sets to test homogeneity in AVERAGE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE

Getting quantile to create the groups

quantile(df_electric_heater$`Average Ambient Temperature`, c(0.25, .5, .75))
##      25%      50%      75% 
## 58.29444 64.89475 70.97595
df_clean %>% 
  group_by(Region) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=`Average Ambient Temperature`, y=Region))+
  geom_boxplot()

Preparing the df and running the test

temp_homo_test <- df_electric_heater %>% 
  group_by(Region) %>% 
  summarise("<58"=sum(`Average Ambient Temperature`<58),
            "58-65"=sum((`Average Ambient Temperature`>=58) & (`Average Ambient Temperature`<65)),
            "65-70"=sum((`Average Ambient Temperature`>=65) & (`Average Ambient Temperature`<70)),
            ">70"=sum(`Average Ambient Temperature`>=70))

temp_homo_test
## # A tibble: 3  5
##   Region `<58` `58-65` `65-70` `>70`
##   <chr>  <int>   <int>   <int> <int>
## 1 NC       186      58      37    60
## 2 RM        37       8       9     9
## 3 SC       206     402     324   440

The test: \[ H_0: The distribution is the same across the groups \] \[ H_1: The distribution is not the same \]

Running the test:

Region NC and RM

chisq.test(temp_homo_test[1:2,2:5])
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  temp_homo_test[1:2, 2:5]
## X-squared = 1.6656, df = 3, p-value = 0.6446

We cannot reject the null hypothesis

Region NC and SC

##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  temp_homo_test[c(1, 3), 2:5]
## X-squared = 242.59, df = 3, p-value < 2.2e-16

We REJECT THE NULL HYPOTHESIS

For all these regressions, we see a NEGATIVE coefficient for Idling time. However, for the linear regressions all coefficients are close, as temperature seems to have little effect in energy consumption. We also see a driving time coefficient close to 45 (this can be compared to the benchmark data that follows).

Plotting observed and predicted values

all_reg_plot <- df_electric_heater %>% 
  select(`Total Energy Consumption`,
         `Idling Time`,
         `Average Ambient Temperature`,
         `Driving Time`)

all_reg_plot <- all_reg_plot %>% 
  mutate(reg1 = fitted.values(reg1),
         reg2 = fitted.values(reg2),
         reg3 = fitted.values(reg3))

all_reg_plot %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = `Total Energy Consumption`, y = reg1))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_abline(intercept=0, slope=1, color="blue") +
  labs(x='Actual Values', y='Predicted Values REG 1', title='Actual vs. Reg1 Predicted Values')

all_reg_plot %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = `Total Energy Consumption`, y = reg2))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_abline(intercept=0, slope=1, color="blue") +
  labs(x='Actual Values', y='Predicted Values REG 2', title='Actual vs. Reg2 Predicted Values')

all_reg_plot %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = `Total Energy Consumption`, y = exp(reg3)))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_abline(intercept=0, slope=1, color="blue") +
  labs(x='Actual Values', y='Predicted Values REG 3', title='Actual vs. Reg3 Predicted Values')

In this case, it makes sense to have idling time with a negative coefficient, since its not consuming any energy from the battery. Driving time coefficient is 31, a little bit less then the observed in the regressions for all regions that use electric heater. It should make difference to add the ambient temperature in this equation but we will test this as well.
